WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.920
Hi everyone, my name is Lydia Gibson and I'm really excited to be here in front of you

00:00:11.920 --> 00:00:17.320
all today talking about a community that's really near and dear to my heart.

00:00:17.320 --> 00:00:22.360
So today I'm going to be talking to you about how the R for Data Science Online Learning

00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:26.600
Community Made Me a Better Student.

00:00:26.600 --> 00:00:35.240
Now a little bit about me, I just graduated with my Masters in Statistics this past May

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:44.279
and then the following month I began working at Intel as a Data Scientist and it's a career

00:00:44.279 --> 00:00:50.919
I never imagined myself in, the same way I never imagined myself standing right in front

00:00:50.919 --> 00:00:58.860
of you all today giving this talk at posit.conf and the reason why is I wanted to be a fashion

00:00:58.860 --> 00:01:01.520
designer when I was younger.

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:10.360
Yeah, so growing up my grandmother used to make matching outfits for my sister and I

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:18.440
and I loved clothing and so in my teens I used to sketch outfits that I would want to

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:26.839
wear, taking inspiration from magazines like Seventeen and Teen Vogue and I even designed

00:01:26.839 --> 00:01:30.879
my own prom dress which my grandmother constructed for me.

00:01:30.879 --> 00:01:39.599
I don't actually know how to sew, but eventually, but yeah so when I started out on my journey

00:01:39.599 --> 00:01:46.519
as far as changing careers, I had no experience programming.

00:01:46.519 --> 00:01:54.320
I am actually 31, I returned to school in my 30s to get my Masters and I didn't have

00:01:54.320 --> 00:02:00.519
experience with statistics for the most part, no former programming experience and I didn't

00:02:00.519 --> 00:02:07.440
care about R, but unfortunately it is a necessary evil if you're going to go back to school

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:17.399
for statistics and I imagine a lot of you also may not have cared about R at some point,

00:02:17.399 --> 00:02:23.320
but yeah, you might not have cared about it, but you did care about the things you can

00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:31.279
do for it, whether it's statistics, biology, something geospatial, eventually you did care

00:02:31.279 --> 00:02:38.119
about it and for me what made me care about it was data visualization.

00:02:38.119 --> 00:02:46.919
So in data visualization I was able to feed my need for that creativity while also still

00:02:46.919 --> 00:02:57.279
learning things that were relevant to what I was doing in my coursework and kind of like

00:02:57.279 --> 00:03:03.440
what Megan mentioned of how it's great to learn when you're doing something that's fun,

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:09.320
it's also great to learn when you have friends to learn with and luckily I was able to find

00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:13.440
that in the R for Data Science online learning community.

00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:20.639
So pictured here with me is John Harmon and he is the Chief Community Manager and Data

00:03:20.639 --> 00:03:28.919
Scientist of the R for Data Science online learning community and him along with his

00:03:28.919 --> 00:03:36.360
merry band of mentors and facilitators, of which I am one, they've created this amazing

00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:45.199
welcoming learning environment, mostly based in Slack, where beginners and advanced folks

00:03:45.199 --> 00:03:51.960
alike can come together and learn various topics not necessarily only related to R but

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:55.399
just data science as a whole.

00:03:55.399 --> 00:04:03.160
So for me, with my interest piqued in data visualization, the most likely choice for

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:12.199
me as far as book clubs was the ggplot2 book club and there in that book club it was me

00:04:12.199 --> 00:04:24.559
statistics, programming, and data viz newbie and I'm there with folks who are R consultants

00:04:24.559 --> 00:04:29.519
and actuaries and PhD students and there's the little old me.

00:04:29.519 --> 00:04:35.239
So honestly it was terrifying, the same way I'm somewhat terrified up here right now,

00:04:35.239 --> 00:04:45.679
but because the way the R community is and R for DS, it was kind of easy to transition

00:04:45.679 --> 00:04:46.799
into it.

00:04:46.799 --> 00:04:53.399
So for me, with my imposter syndrome and just nerves, I decided I'm just going to jump right

00:04:53.399 --> 00:04:59.720
into it and I presented chapter three and actually it's, I just had my two-year anniversary

00:04:59.720 --> 00:05:06.200
of my first presentation.

00:05:06.200 --> 00:05:14.600
It was kind of a basic R markdown presentation, but I did it and I got really great feedback

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:20.559
and everyone was so welcoming and I was just, I fell in love with that community because

00:05:20.559 --> 00:05:27.399
I was able to move past that fear, get out of my comfort zone, and then get in a learning

00:05:27.399 --> 00:05:30.239
zone.

00:05:30.239 --> 00:05:41.519
So and yeah, so by merging my love of like fashion design with data viz, I was just yeah,

00:05:41.519 --> 00:05:45.760
I was just like in love and really into it.

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:52.600
So I was able to take the things I was learning in my book club and put it towards works I

00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:59.480
was doing in classes, being able to not only use like the utility of things you can do

00:05:59.480 --> 00:06:06.640
in Basar, but taking ggplot2 and giving my visualizations a little bit of pizzazz, putting

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:11.160
a little bit of myself into my visualizations.

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:17.559
And obviously the same way in R for DS where it's, you're able to get help from folks,

00:06:17.559 --> 00:06:24.200
I was able to take my visions of what I wanted from my visualizations and with the help of

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:34.600
my friends, especially my friend Ken, be able to create these visualizations that were in

00:06:34.600 --> 00:06:38.119
my head and then put them on the screen.

00:06:38.119 --> 00:06:43.600
And then even through R for DS, I learned about the various extension packages you could

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:50.799
make with ggplot2 and just a whole new world opened up for me.

00:06:50.799 --> 00:06:57.519
And I also learned about the Data Visualization Society and did a mentorship program, just

00:06:57.519 --> 00:07:04.079
feeding my need for that creativity.

00:07:04.079 --> 00:07:13.119
And following that, I eventually ended up doing another book club, facilitating a data

00:07:13.119 --> 00:07:20.000
visualization with our book club by Rob Kabacoff, and even was able to bring in my friends and

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:26.239
teach them things that I had learned, and through that, learning, reinforcing my learning

00:07:26.239 --> 00:07:29.679
as well.

00:07:29.679 --> 00:07:32.959
So then I guess I'll leave you with a couple of takeaways.

00:07:32.959 --> 00:07:38.880
I know this is very short, but yeah, it's kind of like finding what you're passionate

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:45.359
about and exploring its steps, especially as someone new to the field of statistics

00:07:45.359 --> 00:07:51.600
or data science, there's so many tools we could learn, and honestly, it's overwhelming.

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:57.679
So if you can just take that one thing that you're passionate about and explore its steps,

00:07:57.679 --> 00:08:01.399
you can learn so many more things.

00:08:01.399 --> 00:08:06.640
And then being surrounded by folks more advanced than you is a gift, it's not a curse.

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:13.920
It can be scary, it can be overwhelming, and you have this sense of imposter syndrome,

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:21.160
but if you look at it as the opportunity versus that vulnerability, it opens up so many more

00:08:21.160 --> 00:08:23.320
doors for you.

00:08:23.320 --> 00:08:28.359
For example, me even finding out about the Data Visualization Society.

00:08:28.359 --> 00:08:30.959
And then teaching is the best way to learn.

00:08:30.959 --> 00:08:41.840
I've honestly learned so much by facilitating book clubs and just facilitating book clubs

00:08:41.840 --> 00:08:49.719
and having to teach others the things I know and just it being reinforced.

00:08:49.719 --> 00:08:58.919
So this is my friend Ken, and my unofficial motto, I suppose, is always be networking.

00:08:58.919 --> 00:09:04.119
And yeah, I'm like a broken record when it comes to my friends telling them this.

00:09:04.119 --> 00:09:11.679
And it's just because I know how great communities like R4DS, R-Ladies, and generally the R community

00:09:11.679 --> 00:09:18.900
in general is that I think it's so important for folks to get involved, and hopefully my

00:09:18.900 --> 00:09:24.340
talk may have inspired some folks to get involved in R4DS.

00:09:24.340 --> 00:09:28.020
If you want to join, it's r4ds.io slash join.

00:09:28.020 --> 00:09:35.020
If you want to be a mentor, r4ds.io slash join, and ping John the Greek.

00:09:35.020 --> 00:09:44.739
And also if you want to sponsor, to keep communities like this going, so people like me can learn

00:09:44.739 --> 00:09:52.780
and somehow become data scientists like they never envisioned.

00:09:52.780 --> 00:09:53.780
Thank you.

00:09:53.780 --> 00:09:54.780
All right.

00:09:54.780 --> 00:10:06.739
Thank you so much, Lydia.

00:10:06.739 --> 00:10:10.659
So we are taking questions in Slido, which you probably all know at this point, but just

00:10:10.659 --> 00:10:11.659
a reminder.

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:14.700
One question so far.

00:10:14.700 --> 00:10:20.580
What advice would you give to someone who's new to R, but doesn't know where to start

00:10:20.580 --> 00:10:22.299
or what they're interested in?

00:10:22.299 --> 00:10:25.460
R seems vast and overwhelming to explore.

00:10:25.460 --> 00:10:26.460
Discuss.

00:10:26.460 --> 00:10:28.820
It is.

00:10:28.820 --> 00:10:30.780
So where to start?

00:10:30.780 --> 00:10:37.059
As far as starting within the R4DS online community, I actually made a repo.

00:10:37.059 --> 00:10:46.859
So in that third link, I have a repo about information about joining your first R4DS

00:10:46.859 --> 00:10:48.059
book club.

00:10:48.059 --> 00:10:53.979
And I've included things like downloading R, the RStudio IDE, or even getting to Posit

00:10:53.979 --> 00:10:54.979
Cloud.

00:10:54.979 --> 00:11:01.900
And then because R4DS, with our book clubs, we use GitHub, some intro stuff as far as

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:03.580
learning GitHub.

00:11:03.580 --> 00:11:05.900
And just checking out our Slack.

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:12.419
There's so many topics when it comes to R. There's shiny, there's geospatial, anything

00:11:12.419 --> 00:11:14.299
you can think of.

00:11:14.299 --> 00:11:18.020
And just kind of search within there, I would say.

00:11:18.020 --> 00:11:19.020
Okay.

00:11:19.020 --> 00:11:20.020
Fantastic.

00:11:20.020 --> 00:11:21.020
Thank you so much.

00:11:21.020 --> 00:11:21.020


